=Europe=

 Victorian London 
The costermongers of London, England were at their peak in the 19th century. Organised, yet semi-obvious, they were ubiquitous, and their street cries could be heard everywhere.<ref>Chesney, Kellow 1970. ''The Victorian Underworld''. Penguin p43&ndash;56; 97–98.</ref><ref>Mayhew, Henry 1851–1861. ''London Labour and the London Poor''. Researched and written, variously, with J. Binny, B. Hemyng and A. Halliday.</ref>

=Latin America and Caribbean=
File:Chilean street vendors.jpg|thumb|Chilean ''vendedores ambulantes'' in Concepción, Chile|Concepción.
Street vendors in Latin America are known in local Spanish language|Spanish and Portuguese language|Portuguese variously as ''vendedores ambulantes'' ("mobile vendors") or simply ''ambulantes'', a term also used in Italy. In Argentina they are known as ''manteros''. In Brazil, they are also known as "camelôs". Some ''ambulantes'' set up in a fixed location while others are mobile. Some ambulantes sell their goods door-to-door.<ref name=oax>[https://books.google.com/books?id=PFqv3oUyP9IC&pg=PA152&dq=ambulantes&hl=en&sa=X&ei=PJxKU52LAumqsQTFzYG4Bw&ved=0CGUQ6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=ambulantes&f=false] The Peasant Marketing System of Oaxaca, Mexico by Ralph Leon Beals pages 42,</ref> ''Puestos'' are market (place)|market stalls or stands.

Street vendors face various regulations and fees.<ref>cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hfRCAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA328&dq=Vendedores+ambulante&hl=en&sa=X&ei=E5lKU7COH43ksAS934KQAw&ved=0CGIQ6AEwBg#v=onepage&q=Vendedores%20ambulante&f=false |title=Diario de sesiones - Uruguay. Asamblea General. Cαmara de Representantes - Google Books |publisher=Books.google.com |date= |accessdate=2018-03-26</ref>

There are sometimes disputes between established merchants and ambulantes. Bribes are also a problem. Many vendors operate illegally.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=KaXWAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA128&dq=ambulantes&hl=en&sa=X&ei=T6BKU9DrGZDLsQSfzIHQBA&ved=0CE0Q6AEwBjgK#v=onepage&q=ambulantes&f=false Reconstructing Criminality in Latin America] edited by Carlos A. Aguirre, Robert Buffington</ref> In order to avoid overwhelming tourists or shoppers, ambulantes are known to establish territories and limit their numbers. Thieves stealing their goods can be a problem.<ref name=transform>[https://books.google.com/books?id=C2_TWYAKH9cC&pg=PA273&dq=ambulantes&hl=en&sa=X&ei=T6BKU9DrGZDLsQSfzIHQBA&ved=0CFIQ6AEwBzgK#v=onepage&q=ambulantes&f=false Economies and the Transformation of Landscape] edited by Lisa Cliggett, Christopher A. Pool</ref>

Argentina 
File:Manteros en Florida.jpg|thumb|Two Argentine kids working as "manteros" at the Florida Street.
The street vendors in Argentina are known as ''manteros'', after the Spanish word for blanket, ''manta''. They sell varied products in an informal sector|informal way, in most cases placing them over a blanket. They are, in their most part, Illegal immigration in Argentina|illegal immigrants without documents and victims of human trafficking, subject to forced labor.<ref name="mmc">cite web |url= http://www.lanacion.com.ar/1660748-manteros-mafias-y-delitos|title= Manteros, mafias y delitos|trans-title= Manteros, mafias and crimes|language= Spanish|author= |date= February 3, 2014|work= |publisher= La Nación|accessdate=February 12, 2014</ref> They work at the sidewalks of locations with an important daily traffic, such as the Once railway station, the Retiro railway station, and the Florida Street. This commerce poses an illegal competition with the regular retail shops.<ref name="mmc"/> The shops at the Avellaneda street estimated that the presence of ''manteros'' would make them lose 200 million pesos in the Christmas and holiday season.<ref>cite web |url= http://www.lanacion.com.ar/1646795-fores-la-policia-metropolitana-desalojo-a-los-manteros-de-avellaneda-con-balas-de-gomas|title= Flores: la policía metropolitana desalojó a los manteros de Avellaneda con balas de goma|trans-title= Flores: the metropolitan police removed the manteros with rubber bullets|language= Spanish|author= |date= December 11, 2013|work= |publisher= La Nación|accessdate=February 12, 2014</ref>

According to the Confederación Argentina de la Mediana Empresa (CAME), as of December 2013 there were 463 manteros working in Once, 16.8% of the total in Buenos Aires. The daily sales of ''manteros'' are worth 300 million pesos in Buenos Aires, and 52 million in Once. A single ''mantero'' may earn between 2,000 and 3,500 in a day.<ref name="mmc"/> The ''manteros'' are helped by retail shops at other locations, which store their products in the night, even if not allowed to work as warehouses.<ref name="mmc"/>

The government of Buenos Aires tries to eradicate the ''manteros'' with police raids, removing them from the sidewalks and seizing their products. The police also made 35 successful search and seizures at illegal warehouses in January 2014. The ''manteros'', however, return days after the raids. Still, the government attempts to weaken the organizations that back the ''manteros'' with the constant raids.<ref name="mmc"/> The ''manteros'' reacted to the raids with demonstrations.<ref>cite web |url= http://www.lanacion.com.ar/1663603-despues-de-los-cortes-matinales-los-manteros-volvieron-a-protestar-por-la-noche|title= Después de los cortes matinales, los manteros volvieron a protestar por la noche|trans-title= After the blockades in the morning, the manteros renewed their protests in the night|language= Spanish|author= |date= February 12, 2014|work= |publisher= La Nación|accessdate=February 12, 2014</ref>

Brazil
Image:Banca-de-camelô.jpg|thumb|right|Camelô stand in Porto Alegre, Brazil

Camelô is a Brazilian Portuguese name given to street vendors in major Brazilian city|cities.

Law enforcement often enters into conflict – sometimes physical – with camelôs, for selling low-quality products (often imported from Asia), making improper use of public space (blocking sidewalks and pedestrian traffic), and for not paying the same taxes that licensed retailers pay. Their presence is considered to be a result of the alarming rise in unemployment, although their lifestyle might be better referred to as "subemployment." Many people who work as camelôs sell their products knowing that they are of low quality, and charge high prices nonetheless.

The word is borrowed from the French language|French ''camelot,'' meaning "merchant of low-quality goods," and the term ''marreteiro'' is also sometimes used. The difference between camelôs and so-called "ambulantes" is that camelôs have fixed "storefronts" on a particular sidewalk, whereas "ambulantes" sell their wares throughout an area.

Caribbean
In the English-speaking Caribbean, hawkers are commonly referred to as higglers or informal commercial importers.<ref>[http://www.jamaicans.com/speakja/glossary.htm Jamaica Glossary of Terms] webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110911025113/http://www.jamaicans.com/speakja/glossary.htm |date=September 11, 2011 </ref>  They sell items in small roadside stands, public transit hubs, or other places where consumers would want items such as snacks, cigarettes, phone cards, or other less expensive items.  Higglers often break larger items into small individual consumable portions for re-sale and use. Buying these items from more traditional vendors, farmers, or merchants for re-sale via their informal network in communities <ref>[https://www.jstor.org/stable/2235264?seq=1 The Economic Journal: A Theory of Petty Trading: The Jamaican Higgler]</ref>

Cuba
In Cuban music and Latin American music, a pregón (announcement or street-seller's cry) is a type of song based on the hawking by street vendor of their goods ("canto de los vendedores ambulantes").<ref>Giro, Radamés 2007. ''Diccionario enciclopédico de la música en Cuba''. La Habana. vol 3, p262.</ref>

Guatemala
In Antigua Guatemala|Antigua, women, many from  the Maya peoples|Maya (including Kaqchikel people) and Ladino people|Ladino ethnic groups, peddle handicrafts. Some sell textiles such a po't (blouses) and su't.<ref name=transform/>

Mexico
The presence of Street vendors in Mexico City dates to the pre-Hispanic era and the government has struggled to control it, with the most recent clearing of downtown streets of vendors occurring in 2007. Still, there is a persistent presence of many thousands illegally.<ref name=mas13>[http://www.maspormas.com/nacion-df/df/toreros-un-mal-del-centro-historico#sthash.7zwesfil.dpuf "“Toreros”, un mal del Centro Histórico", ''Más por Más", February 18, 2013]</ref> In 2003 it was estimated that there were 199,328 street vendors in Mexico City.<ref name=gomez>[https://www.academia.edu/937299/Redes_sociales_y_comercio_en_via_publica_en_la_Ciudad_de_Mexico ''Redes sociales y comercio en vía pública en la Ciudad de México'', Norma Gómez Méndez]</ref>

In Oaxaca, Oaxaca|Oaxaca, Mexico there are many tortilla vendors.<ref name=oax/> In Oaxaca the term regatones (hagglers) is used for those who buy goods to resell for a profit.

Peru
In Peru, water cannon were used against the ambulantes in Arequipa, Peru. Many of the ambulantes come from rural areas to sell their goods including prickly pear cactus, bordados (embroideries) and polleras (embroidered skirts).<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=0h5sgum_ElYC&pg=PA8&dq=ambulantes&hl=en&sa=X&ei=T6BKU9DrGZDLsQSfzIHQBA&ved=0CEIQ6AEwBDgK#v=onepage&q=ambulantes&f=false Gender and the Boundaries of Dress in Contemporary Peru] by Blenda Femenías</ref>

